## [x] Abuse control and concurrency hardening are now implemented

Current code evidence
- server.js now enforces actor-scoped mutation rate limits across function invocation, runtime mutation, audit write, and Git mutation lanes.
- server.js now enforces workspace mutation locks so concurrent runtime and Git mutations cannot mutate the same workspace at the same time.
- scripts/verify-hardening.js proves one concurrent workspace mutation is rejected with 423 workspace.locked and repeated mutation writes are throttled with 429 mutation.rate_limited before recovering after the rate window.
- package.json now includes verify:hardening.
- scripts/verify-critical.js now includes verify:hardening.

Code implication
- Concurrent runtime, Git, and release mutations now have a serialized workspace mutation boundary.
- Repeated caller abuse now hits enforced pressure control instead of hammering expensive mutation lanes unchecked.
- Abuse control and concurrency hardening are no longer blockers to unattended autonomous use.

## What Is Not Blocking Anymore

These surfaces are already represented in code and verification:
- Runtime ownership and lifecycle
- Container-backed runtime verification
- Crash recovery verification
- Secrets rotation, revoke, and inventory verification
- Structured audit logging verification
- Role-aware access enforcement across runtime, Git, and release mutation lanes
- Shell partialization and workspace UI modularity

## Current Bottom Line

SkyDexia is not blocked by missing UI polish. After shipping deferred mail continuity, executable release replay proof, executable fallback proof, soak proof, storage migration/versioning, abuse control and concurrency hardening, and full critical-gate coverage for existing verifiers, the implementation surfaces tracked in this file are now closed.

